<section xml:id="section-jordan-terminology">

<title>Terminology and notation</title>

<p><dl>

	<li>
	<title>Jordan block</title>
	<idx><h>Jordan</h><h>block</h></idx>
	<idx><h>block</h><h>Jordan</h></idx>
	<p>
	a square matrix of the form
	<me>
		J(\lambda)
		= \begin{bmatrix}
			\lambda \\
			1 \amp \lambda \\
			\amp \ddots \amp \ddots \\
			\amp \amp 1 \amp \lambda
		\end{bmatrix}
	</me>
	</p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

<p><dl>

	<li>
	<title>Jordan normal form</title>
	<idx><h>Jordan</h><h>normal form</h></idx>
	<idx><h>form</h><h>Jordan normal form</h></idx>
	<p>
	a matrix in block-diagonal form,
	where every block is a Jordan block and all blocks with the same diagonal entry <m>\lambda</m> appear consecutively in order of descending size
	</p>
	</li>

</dl></p>

<remark><p>
	The condition that all blocks with the same diagonal entry <m>\lambda_j</m> appear in descending size is often left out of the definition of the form in other references.
	We have included it for <q>uniqueness</q> reasons.
	(See <xref ref="subsection-jordan-concepts-form-unique" />.)
</p></remark>


</section>
